editorial_summary.overview: Baroque residence housing children's, fashion & ceramics museums with manicured gardens.

reviews.text: Had the most amazing morning exploring the grounds of this palace. It was during December and I think because it was winter we didn’t have to pay any entrance fees. The palace also wasn’t open to go inside. But it had snowed and the gardens were just beautiful.
Amazing guided tour, very informative and entertaining. The castle has been kept in an excellent condition. The ticket is separate than the surrounding garden which is joyful for if you have kids.

If you enjoy historical tours this one is fairly quick and reasonably priced. The guide in English was very knowledgeable. Note that you can only do the tour at certain times of day. I recommend going through the gardens as well which needs several hours to explore.

The place is very beautiful and the architecture and arts are also awesome. Highly recommended place if you are in Stuttgart for half a day. The ticket includes a guided tour in both English and German. Danke!

Really interesting Residential, we paid for the tour and it was entertaining. We also visited the gardens (there’s an extra fee for that) would recommend more to visit once it’s spring or summer. It can be very entertaining for kids since they have sets for different classical fairytales.

editorial_summary.overview: Originally built in the 10th century, this castle houses part of the Württemberg State Museum.

reviews.text: The museum only costed 6 Euros, and there are so many things to see inside! It is so worth it. Highly recommended!

This is a museum full of very important and distinguished works that surprised me. It was a museum filled with a variety of jewellery, everyday items, paleolithic, neolithic, Roman, Celtic… artifacts of higher quality than I expected.
Entry is free throughout 2020, if you like visiting museums, you can easily spend two or three hours. Although a part of it was under restoration when I went, even this much was magnificent.
The explanations are in German, but what the dazzling things are can be understood from the drawings or animations.
Ethnographic artifacts and items from historical churches were also on display.
The quality of the museum was evident even from its stylish staff in suits.
Apart from the exhibits, if you have time and interest, I recommend you to examine the lower drawers in some sections, I would definitely recommend you to visit this museum!
Real cool museum. Lots of things to see. I really liked the religious art.

The museum is very beautiful and the exhibition is explained in detail, even for children! The staff is very attentive, helpful and friendly. We were there just before closing time, but we were politely received and translated answered. The building itself is very well preserved and also without a museum worth seeing!
Absolutely stunning! You have to see it 😍

editorial_summary.overview: Built 1764–1769, the rococo-style palace of Duke Carl Eugen offers an eatery, hiking trails & views.

reviews.text: Went there to take pictures for my school dance! I loved the area and was beautiful a lot of kids come here for their school prom pictures
Such an amazing place for the views, the peace and quiet, and to relax. I really enjoy the views over the city from here, and I especially love that it's never crowded when I visit

I gave it 5 stars for the historical reasons, the palace itself inside was small in my opinion but very beautiful. You can't go on your own and explore the inside you have to purchase tickets (6 per adult and 3 per student) but they do offer a family pack and this is with a tour in German. They do, however, give you an English pamphlet to read in regards to the rooms you will be seeing. Please check the website to see at what time the tours take place. The grounds are nicely maintained, and you will have beautiful vista's. Plenty of pictures to take, for the grounds are big. Bring your walking shoes.

Awesome place located in the higher altitude  in the mid of no where. Romantic view in the evening. Good for marriage photography as well as half day tour. You can have a view of the city for the palace top.
Beautiful, clean, picturesque and peaceful. Not too many visitors when I went there.

Super
Freaking awesome!

Old Renaissance castle, former widow's residence of the Württemberg dukes and kings. Today it is used as a state educational seminar, as a museum and as an event location. Nice little park, the Marstallgarten and accessible moat with children's playground. Castle chapel is used as a concert hall.

Celebrated daughter's wedding here. A very nice and stylish location to celebrate.
Unfortunately, the room, which is not too large, has no air conditioning, so that with just over 100 people dancing, you don't have to sweat. The toilet facilities could have been bigger.

Very nice wedding location! I attended a wedding there with my band last year. There were a few small problems with the acoustics, but in the end it was an extremely successful party with a very nice flair! Great space and great service! =)

Really impressive location for parties. The caretaker is super friendly and the location is also very attractive in terms of price. Unfortunately, you have to reserve very early, usually more than a year in advance. There is no kitchen, but there is a spacious bar for each room to serve guests. The premises are an absolute dream and have a very nice flair.

It's definitely worth taking a look here if you're flexible with your appointment.
Very nice historic building. Excellently restored.

I have photographed several weddings here over the years and I am always amazed. Very nice courtyard for the champagne reception and exciting rooms for celebrations in a modern-rustic style. It's a bit up the mountain, on the outer edge of Köngen, so quiet. Definitely a recommendation for a great wedding!

editorial_summary.overview: This historic castle with a courtyard garden is a popular place for sweeping views of Esslingen.

name: Esslingen am Neckar Castle

reviews.text:
Very very calm and peaceful place. The way up the hill and the exploring the places nearby was a great experience and the View was absolutely gorgeous 🥰🥰
Great place for picnics, quality time and they even have a play area for kids 👶
This castle is easy to get to and worth visiting. There are at least three ways to get up to it. I love the steps up through the walls, the vineyards and the views.

Didn’t even realise that this was the castle when we were there. But definitely go up the long flight of stairs on the city wall - the views over the city and vineyards and breathtaking! We happened upon this stairway by chance. We were in Esslingen over December and it had snowed, so everything was dusted in snow. We spent a good afternoon exploring this area! This whole town is just magical - with its cobblestone streets, gorgeous gingerbread style houses and stunning views. It’s well worth stopping in Esslingen for a day to explore!

A must-see place when you visit Esslingen am Neckar. From Esslingen Hbf, you can take Bus 110 and drop by Esslingen (N) Burg bus stop. A 10-minute walk leads you to this place. Alternatively, you can take any buses from the Esslingen Hbf that pass by Berliner Straße and drop by Esslingen (N) Marktplatz stop. From there, you can take the several steep steps leading up the hill to reach the castle. A more physically challenging route, but definitely worth it. Up there, you can enjoy the magnificent view of the city of Esslingen below.
A good place to play frisbee. To climb up from Esslingen city centre to the castle is tiring. But it worth.

Formerly a unit of church building from the old castle and from the new building once had a ring wall around everything. Originated from a castle that probably only consisted of a stone house. Has been rebuilt and rebuilt over and over again. Behind it is the palace park. Some of the buildings are privately owned and occupied by the town hall, so they are closed. The complex forms an ensemble worth seeing. It is not possible to park on the old school square, so use the Lindenstraße car park next to the bakery.
A beautiful and well-kept place. Unfortunately, no visit was possible. We went to the park. It is also very beautiful. Have a nice Sunday afternoon.

Wow, one can only marvel here. For a small community, a beautiful castle with an idyllic garden is not to be expected. Here the castle and the church are beautiful. You can admire the architecture. The gardens were also designed very nicely. Absolutely gorgeous.

A beautiful old castle with a great garden. Here is the town hall. Parking lots nearby. A café or the super ice cream parlor are also within walking distance. Hemmingen has some well-preserved half-timbered houses in the center. You can also arrive by bus or the Strohgäu Bahn, worth a visit.

Nice little castle in Hemmingen.
The town hall is also there.
Adjacent a small nice park.

Leonberg Castle
“When the city was founded, the Counts of Württemberg built a castle on the south-west corner. Between 1560 and 1565, Leonberg Palace was essentially given its present form by reconstruction under Duke Christoph. The coats of arms of Saxony-Anhalt and Württemberg on the underside of the bay window are reminiscent of Duchess Sibylla, who spent her widowhood in the palace.
Duke Karl Eugen's attempt to sell the castle in 1765 failed due to the lack of financial strength of the Leonberg citizenry.
It is therefore still owned by the state today: the district court and tax office are housed here.
Please note: Leonberg Castle cannot be visited.”
A very beautiful place. I am delighted
All very good 👌
Very nice views and parks.

The castle is one of the symbols of the city. It is located on the outskirts of the old town and invites you to stroll and linger with its adjoining bitter orange garden. Unfortunately, you cannot visit the castle itself, as the district court and the tax office of Leonberg are located there today. So if you explore the beautiful old town of Leonberg, you should definitely stop by the castle!

reviews.text: I can’t believe I finally got to see the interior of the New Palace in Stuttgart. It’s not open to the public except on the night of the open museums. I cannot recommend doing that more. So beautiful and so opulent.

The footprint of this palace is pretty huge and it spreads in a nig area with lots of gardens and public squares around. Very close to the Stuttgart main station and one of the most visited spots in this city...

The building with the Stag on top is also a rare sight.

The palace is lit during Christmas and New year's. Even otherwise, it's an exquisite spot in the bang in the middle of Stuttgart city. Thi surroundings are amazing to enjoy and relax with lots of city hush-hush and on the contrary, greeny around the lake behind the Schloss.
I don’t understand what the hype was but I wasn’t even allowed to go inside this palace. It’s just a building form outside

The main attraction of this place though is the view. It's lovely.

After the castles sunk into insignificance, i.e. after the use of cannons, the rulers preferred to move to more comfortable castles. Here, next to the castle, a manor house with a palace, farmyard and the usual buildings for a manor was built. Of course, a castle park could not be missing. The palace and park are privately owned. So they are not open to the public. However, the park is partially opened on Heritage Days. If you want to get to the castle ruins, you have to go through the palace complex. Don't plan to park in the castle, it's closed, and the roadside was also blocked with stones on the driveway. So drive in the direction of the golf car park and park there on the right-hand side of the access road. Then walk to the castle, the upper path along the park wall over the golf course is closed. So down long is better.
